text: 1‑Alkoxyvinyl Ester as an Excellent Acyl Donor: Eﬃcient Macrolactone Synthesis Yasuyuki Kita,* Shuji Akai, Hiromichi Fujioka, and Tohru Kamitanaka ABSTRACT: Ketene acetal derivatives, such as 1-alkoxyvinyl esters and O-silyl ketene acetals, belong to the category of O-substituted enols of esters, which easily react with various types of nucleophiles, Nu−H, under neutral conditions to give the corresponding acylated and silylated products in excellent yields only by evaporation of the generated volatile esters. Silyl ketene acetals can be easily synthesized by various simple procedures, whereas 1-alkoxyvinyl esters require an equimolar or catalytic amount of a mercury salt to synthesize them. This drawback prevented the advancement of the chemistry of 1- alkoxyvinyl esters. In 1993, we developed a useful synthetic method of 1-alkoxyvinyl esters using a small amount (0.5−1 mol %) of a ruthenium catalyst. Encouraged by this discovery, we subsequently developed various reactions and applied them to the synthesis of natural products. It is noteworthy that the stereoselective total synthesis of fredericamycin A was achieved by the combined use of these reactions. Macrocyclization was variously utilized for the synthesis of natural macrolides by two types of approaches: direct macrolactonization of α,ω-hydroxy acids or intermolecular esteriﬁcation between an acid and alcohol followed by a ring-closure step. Additionally, several new reactions using 1-alkoxyvinyl esters or their analogs as key intermediates on the basis of our methods were recently reported. In this paper, we introduce our eﬀorts from the synthesis of 1-alkoxyvinyl esters to the application such as natural product syntheses and recent advancements.

Group transfer reactions, which proceed under neutral or nearly neutral conditions, are important process in organic synthesis. These are especially beneﬁcial for the synthesis of complex molecules, such as natural products, since such mild reactions do not aﬀect other functional groups in the molecule. Speciﬁcally, a basic reaction causes epimerization and elimination side reactions. In this context, we have studied various unique reactions and applied them to the synthesis of natural products. In particular, silyl- or acyl-transfer reactions using ketene acetals are typical examples for our developed neutral and versatile reactions (Scheme 1). These reactions Scheme 1. Additionally, the sole byproduct, i.e., an ester, can be easily removed by evaporation after the reaction. Our studies of ketene acetals started in Büchi’s laboratory at MIT (1975). In the study of the total synthesis of vinblastine, the acetylation of the tertiary alcohol on velbanamine was required for the coupling with vindoline and accomplished by utilization of isopropenyl acetate in the presence of a catalytic amount of p-toluenesulfonic acid (Scheme 2, eq 1). Any other acetylation reagents with pyridine, DMAP, KH, and AgOTf, among others, did not produce the desired acetylation. In contrast, a similar type of reagents, O-silyl ketene acetals, have been extensively studied by various researchers due to the ease of synthesis. Although these cases focused on the reactivity of the nucleophilic oleﬁn moiety, we focused on the electrophilicity of the silyl groups on the O-silyl ketene acetals due to the aforementioned reactivity and ﬁrst reported silylation of alcohols, carboxylic acids, and thiols.11−13 Subsequently, we reported the silyl group transfer 1,4-addition to α,β-unsaturated carbonyls,14,15 1,2-addition to alde- hydes,16,17 1,3-addition to nitrones,18−20 stereoselective Pummerer-type reactions,21−25 and substitution into quinone monoacetals26 (Scheme 4). APPLICATIONS 2.1. Development of New Method for Synthesis of 1- Alkoxyvinyl Esters and Acylation. Over the past four decades, we have studied the utilization of 1-alkoxyvinyl esters as eﬃcient reagents for various reactions. In the early studies, the acylation,4,8 1-alkoxyvinyl esters were utilized for Semmler−Wolﬀ aromatization,6 and synthesis of carboxylic anhydrides.7,8 Although the synthetic method of 1-alkoxyvinyl esters was reported more than 60 years ago,9,10 it had not received much attention for a long time. The most important reason for the lack of its utility might be the necessity of using a mercury salt for the synthesis of the 1-alkoxyvinyl esters from alkoxyacetylene and carboxylic acids. However, we discovered an alternative method for the synthesis of EVEs by using a ruthenium catalyst in 1993 (Scheme 6).30,31 This method has some advantages in the synthetic aspects: (1) Only a small amount of a catalyst is needed. (2) Various carboxylic acids having a highly reactive functional group tolerate this reaction (Table 1). (3) Generation of a byproduct, such as an anhydride, is less than previous methods. (4) In the case of unstable derivatives, EVEs can be used directly for the next reaction without puriﬁcation. We also reported the utility of the obtained EVEs as acyl donors for alcohols or amines under neutral or nearly neutral conditions (Scheme 7).30,31 This reaction proceeds under mild conditions, and the sole byproduct, ethyl acetate, is easily removed by simple evaporation after the reaction. 2.2. Enzymatic Kinetic Resolution. Enzymatic acylation is recognized as one eﬀective stereoselective method in organic synthesis. Although vinyl esters are commonly used as an acyl donor they generate the toxic acetaldehyde as byproduct, and it is known to deactivate some kinds of enzymes.36 Therefore, we assumed that EVEs could serve as alternative acyl donors because EVEs generate a less harmful byproduct, ethyl acetate. We ﬁrst tried the kinetic resolution of racemic sec-alcohols by the combined use of 1- ethoxyvinyl acetate and lipase (Scheme 8, eq 1).37 This reaction aﬀorded acylated products in high yields for one enantiomer under mild conditions, and the other enantiomer was recovered as an unreacted alcohol. Kretzschmar et al. also studied and reported a very similar reaction at almost the same time.38 https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.joc.0c02677 J. Org. Enzymatic Reactions Next, we reported the domino-type reaction from racemic furfuryl alcohols and ethoxyvinyl methyl fumarate in the presence of lipase (Scheme 8, eq 2).39,40 In this reaction, one enantiomer was selectively acylated and the acylated product was transformed into fused ring systems by the intramolecular Diels−Alder reaction. Moreover, we developed the one-pot the EVEs,41 enabling the reaction without application of unstable EVEs to this domino-type reaction.

These methods could aﬀord acylated products in high optical yields. However, a speciﬁc limitation of the kinetic resolution is the atom-economy aspect, that is, the maximum yield is 50%. To overcome this, a racemization pre-equilibrium would permit quantitative yield in the process of dynamic kinetic resolution (DKR). Therefore, we subsequently reported the DKR and the following Diels−Alder reaction for the synthesis of optically active polysubstituted decalins, which could aﬀord the desired product in up to 100% yield (Scheme 8, eq 3).42 The most important point of the success of this DKR is the ruthenium-catalyzed racemization of an alcohol. Furthermore, we reported the chemo- and stereo- selective acylation by the vanadium-catalyzed DKR.43 We applied these ﬁndings to the stereoselective total synthesis of natural products, i.e., (−)-rosmarinecine (Scheme 8, eq 4)44,45 and (−)-himbacine (Scheme 8, eq 5).46 We ﬁrst achieved the total synthesis of (−)-rosmarinecine in 6 steps.44 Our subsequent investigation enabled the reduction of the synthetic steps by protecting group-free approach.45 The stereoselective total synthesis of (−)-himbacine was achieved by the combined use of lipase and mesoporous-silica- immobilized oxovanadium.46 The lipase-catalyzed acylation could be utilized not only in these kinetic resolutions but also in the desymmetrization of diols.41,47,48 Although various types of acyl groups were introduced, the desymmetrized products of 2,2-disubstituted https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.joc.0c02677 J. Pummerer-Type Reaction. 2.3.1. Asymmetric Pum- merer-Type Reaction. The Pummerer reaction is a useful method for the synthesis of α-acyloxy sulﬁdes from sulfoxides. In general, carboxylic anhydrides or acyl halides are utilized as an initiator of the reaction. However, a stereoselective reaction is diﬃcult to realize because this reaction generates the sulfurane intermediate. Meanwhile, we succeeded in the stereoselective Pummerer-type reaction by using O-silyl ketene acetals as the initiator. The key to success of the stereoselective reaction are the mild conditions which do not generate the sulfonium ion intermediate and proceed via the three- membered ring transition state.23,52 In the same manner as used in these previous studies, we succeeded in the stereoselective Pummerer-type reaction by using EVEs as the initiator, and α-acetoxysulﬁdes could be obtained (Scheme 9).53,54 It was assumed that this reaction also does not generate a sulfonium ion intermediate and that it proceeds via ﬁve- membered ring (cyclic mode) and/or three-membered ring (sliding mode) transition states. 2.3.2. MACROLACTONE SYNTHESIS Macrolactones exist in not only as various natural products but also as many pharmaceutical compounds.66 Various synthetic approaches to the construction of the macrolactone ring have been developed, which can be divided in two types. One is the direct macrolactonization of α,ω-hydroxy acid by an intra- molecular esteriﬁcation (Scheme 15, Type A). The other is the Scheme 15. Two Types of Macrolactonization

intermolecular esteriﬁcation of an alcohol and a carboxylic acid which is followed by a diﬀerent type of ring closure, after forming a C−C bond in this subsequent step (Type B).66,67 The Type A macrolactonization approach, represented by the Yamaguchi,68 Shiina,69 Corey−Nicolaou,70 and Keck71 reactions, has been widely used in the synthesis of natural products because of the mild conditions. Although a 14- membered macrolactone was obtained in acceptable yield, a considerable amount of dimer was obtained. In contrast, larger ring sizes (15−22 members) were obtained in good yields. We have developed the EVE-mediated eﬃcient esteriﬁcation as previously mentioned. Several years later, our group expanded the scope of this macrocyclization approach by changing of the reaction conditions (Scheme 17).73 The key variable that resulted in improved yield was the choice of solvent (DCE vs toluene). This eﬀective method gave a new option for the construction of the macrolactone and was sometimes called the “Kita esteriﬁcation” or “Kita−Trost macrolactonization”. Various research groups utilized this macrolactonization for the synthetic study of macrolides and achieved the synthesis of natural products as described below.

We ﬁrst show natural product syntheses by the Type A macrolactonization approach (Table 3). The ﬁrst example of a natural product synthesis using this method was the total synthesis of cochleamycin A reported by Tatsuta et al. (entry 1).74 In 2004, Maier et al. reported the total synthesis of apicularen A (entry 2). In this example, the size-selective macrolactonization proceeded though two free hydroxy groups exist in the molecule.75 Lee et al. reported the total synthesis of amphidinolide E in 2006 (entry 3).76−78 In this case, the macrolactone ring was constructed without epimerization of the methyl group at the α-position of the carbonyl group. Mohapatra et al. reported the synthesis of the amphidinolide W analog (entry 4). When they tried the Yamaguchi macrolactonization, the cyclized product was obtained as a mixture of stereoisomers at the α-position of the carbonyl group. In contrast, the present EVE-method gave a single isomer of the desired product.79,80 The total syntheses of (−)-dactylolideand and (−)-zampanolide were reported by Uenishi et al. in 2009 (entry 5).81 In this report, hydroxy acid was constructed by the coupling of two fragments using the Horner−Emmons reaction, and the following EVE method successfully gave the macrolactone ring. In the total synthesis of (−)-seimatopolide, the macrolactone was obtained in 72% yield by the present EVE method, and the following deprotection of the MOM group aﬀorded the natural product (entry 6).82 In this study, the Yamaguchi macrolactonization was also conducted, but the product was obtained in only a moderate yield (51%). In 2015, Boland et al. reported the synthesis of the JA-Ile-lactone from methyl jasmonate by a 7- step sequence (entry 7).83 The present EVE method was utilized in the last step and gave the JA-Ile-lactone in 64% yield.

In this section, we introduced the utilization of the EVE- mediated method for the intermolecular esteriﬁcation step in several synthetic studies of natural products. It is noteworthy that all of these cases achieved the esteriﬁcation of the α,β- unsaturated carboxylic acids without any eﬀect on this reactive double bond. These examples successfully show the availability of the present EVE-mediated reaction for the synthesis of complex molecules. 4. CONCLUSION The development of an eﬃcient acylation and other several applications using 1-alkoxyvinyl esters are described. These

reactions proceeded under neutral or nearly neutral conditions, and the sole byproduct, ethyl acetate, could be easily removed by concentration after the reaction. These advantages enabled the synthesis of unstable or complex molecules, such as the quinone mono O,S-acetal, fredericamycin A, and macro- lactones. Notably, the macrolactonization was used for the synthesis of various natural products by other research groups. Fortunately, these EVE-mediated reactions were recognized as important methods for the synthesis of complex molecules and are sometimes introduced as the “Kita esteriﬁcation” in research papers, presentations, and the web (Chem-Station: https://en.chem-station.com/). We expect that acylation and other various reactions using 1-alkoxyvinyl esters will make further progress and contribute to advancements in organic chemistry. Tohru Kamitanaka was born in 1984 in Shiga, Japan. He studied organic chemistry at the Graduate School of Life Sciences, Ritsumeikan University and received his Ph.D. in 2015 under the supervision of Professor Yasuyuki Kita. During this term, he was appointed as JSPS Research Fellow (DC2 and PD). After two years of postdoctoral work, he was promoted to Assistant Professor at Ritsumeikan University. His current research interests include the synthesis of multifunctionalized aromatic compounds using quinone monoacetals and the synthesis of various biologically active compounds. The authors are grateful to Specially Appointed Professor Junichi Haruta of Osaka University, Professor Osamu Tamura of Showa Pharmaceutical University, Professor Norio Shibata of Nagoya Institute of Technology, Professor Shinji Kitagaki and Masato Matsugi of Meijo University, Dr. Hiroshi Maeda, Dr. Yusuke Ohba, and all of the co-workers who have contributed to this chemistry.
